metadata.name: TI·ME 0 #75
metadata.description:
How and when Time started has always been one of the biggest questions of the humankind, that is yet to be answered.

There are things we may know, and there are things we may never know. Though, one thing that may be considered as certain is that, it did not start before it was started to be measured.

* * *

This generative artwork is a gift to my dear collectors of TI·ME series (TI·ME I, TI·ME II & TI·ME III).

Any collector who is holding 3 or more pieces of any of the three TI·ME collections mentioned above at the snapshot time of Aug 22, 18:00 UTC, will receive a piece from TI·ME 0 sent to their wallet. One piece per each 3 pieces held, i.e., if you have 9 pieces in total from any TI·ME collections combined, you will receive 3 pieces. Remaining pieces (if any), will be sent to randomly selected collectors who have less than 3 pieces.

Thank you very much for collecting and for your continuous support. Only with that, I can continue to do what I love.

Press S to save as PNG.

Made by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART

metadata.name: Crash Euphoria #60
metadata.description:
My first foray into shaders and GLSL: This piece experiments with layering many textures guided by an underlying pattern. Each pixel value dictates which pattern is displayed. There are varying levels of imperfections in each pattern, some choose a single color, some use a color guide pattern, some individual strokes decide on another color altogether. These layers are compiled in a shader and warped.

Press 's' in live view to save a png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Satisfying Grids #121
metadata.description:
Believe it or not, this project started as... well... a Blob. 

Polar coordinates mixed with Perlin Noise were used to draw an ever morphing blobby shape, walking around the canvas... living the life of it's own. 
Soon enough, my drawing skills had reached their limits, and the Blob forever disappeared from the face of this Earth. 

A grid emerged, using the same polar coordinates at different points of the canvas, progressively filling it, in a satisfying but sometimes OCD triggering manner. 

Features include Grid Size, Sub Grid Size and Speed.
300 colour palettes were used in the making of this. 

Enjoy !

This was created using the p5js library.

metadata.name: Sideral Wind #24
metadata.description:
"Sideral" is archaic for "sidereal" and it means: emanating from the stars and especially from stars held to be malefic. Sideral Wind is an interstellar force that comes from evil celestial worlds and that can take the form of strong thunderstorms hitting and sweeping any planet in its way or generating alien bodies in the sky.

- hit 's' and save the svg file at the current resolution of display
- hit 'p' and save the png file at 3072px x 3072px

metadata.name: Tuesday #118
metadata.description: Maybe it's inspired by the marks left by coffee cups in my notebook. Maybe the doodles in that same notebook, often squares and circles, somehow influenced this work. Maybe the Bridget Riley book sitting on the shelf above gently whispered to me when I wasn't looking. Or maybe I just played with an idea and found it pleasing. The only thing I'm certain of – it was definitely a Tuesday.

metadata.name: Ari's Thread #118
metadata.description:
I side with the idea that we made this reality so weird merely to satisfy our -psychotic- need to overcomplicate things. Not you, of course.

That's why I believe that our choices don't "create our own path" but a maze for others to (try to) solve.
This God or that One or none, the old songs or the new ones, rooting for or against…
The deepest we meet into each other's maze, the more choices we share. Reciprocally, when we lack the interest to explore even a couple of turns, we're but a first impression to each other.

This work examines those ideas by continually presenting options to N individuals and then tracking their choices, which in turn generates different outputs at different depths.

To access them:
- press "S" for story mode, the sequence of choices
  - then, press "1" through "5" to change the speed
- press "L" for landscape, the first impression
- press "D" to see the details and view the mazes (may take a while)
